SIMPLE: sport
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sport
<hw>Sport</hw> <pr>(sp⟦omac⟧rt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbreviated
from <ets>disport</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which diverts, and
makes mirth; pastime; amusement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is as <qex>sport</qex> to a fool to do mischief.</q>
<rj><qau>Prov. x. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her <qex>sports</qex> were such as carried riches of knowledge
upon the stream of delight.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Think it but a minute spent in <qex>sport</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mock; mockery; contemptuous mirth;
derision.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then make <qex>sport</qex> at me; then let me be your jest.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That with which one plays, or which is driven about
in play; a toy; a plaything; an object of mockery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Flitting leaves, the <qex>sport</qex> of every wind.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Never does man appear to greater disadvantage than when he is the
<qex>sport</qex> of his own ungoverned passions.</q> <rj><qau>John
Clarke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Play; idle jingle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An author who should introduce such a <qex>sport</qex> of words
upon our stage would meet with small applause.</q>
<rj><qau>Broome.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Diversion of the field, as fowling, hunting,
fishing, racing, games, and the like, esp. when money is
staked.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Bot. & Zool.)</fld> <def>A plant or an animal, or
part of a plant or animal, which has some peculiarity not usually seen
in the species; an abnormal variety or growth. See <cref>Sporting
plant</cref>, under <er>Sporting</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A sportsman; a gambler.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In sport</b></col>, <cd>in jest; for play or
diversion.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧So is the man that deceiveth his neighbor, and
saith, Am not I <xex>in sport</xex>?⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Prov. xxvi.
19.</au></rj> </cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Play; game; diversion; frolic; mirth; mock;
mockery; jeer.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sport</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sport
<hw>Sport</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sported</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sporting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To play; to frolic;
to wanton.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Fish], <qex>sporting</qex> with quick glance,⟦br⟧
Show to the sun their waved coats dropt with gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To practice the diversions of the field or the turf;
to be given to betting, as upon races.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To trifle.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧He <xex>sports</xex> with
his own life.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Tillotson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Bot. & Zool.)</fld> <def>To assume suddenly a new
and different character from the rest of the plant or from the type of
the species; -- said of a bud, shoot, plant, or animal. See
<er>Sport</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 6.</def> <rj><au>Darwin.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To play; frolic; game; wanton.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sport</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sport
<hw>Sport</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To divert; to amuse;
to make merry; -- used with the reciprocal pronoun.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Against whom do ye <qex>sport</qex> yourselves?</q> <rj><qau>Isa.
lvii. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To represent by any kind of play.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now <qex>sporting</qex> on thy lyre the loves of youth.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To exhibit, or bring out, in public; to use or wear;
<as>as, to <ex>sport</ex> a new equipage</as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>Grose.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To give utterance to in a sportive manner; to throw
out in an easy and copious manner; -- with <xex>off</xex>; <as>as, to
<ex>sport</ex> off epigrams</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To sport one's oak</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Oak</er>,
<pos>n.</pos></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sportability</ent>⟦br⟧
